def can_transform(s, t):
    i, j = 0, 0
    while i < len(s) and j < len(t):
        if s[i] == t[j]:
            i += 1
            j += 1
        else:
            i += 1
    return j == len(t)
```


    The algorithm used in all these implementations is the same. We use two pointers `i` and `j` to iterate through string `s` and `t`, respectively. We start at the beginning of each string and compare the characters at `i` and `j` indices. 

If the characters are the same, we increment both `i` and `j`. If the characters are different, we increment only `i`, which effectively deletes the character at index `i` from string `s`. 

We repeat this process until we have iterated through the entire string `s` or string `t`. If we've reached the end of string `t`, it means we could possibly transform `s` into `t` by visiting/deleting some characters from `s`. In this case, we return `true`. If we haven't reached the end of string `t`, it means we couldn't transform `s` into `t`, and we return `false`. 

For all languages, the implementation and logic are the same, only the syntax differs. For example, in Python, we use `len()` to find the length of a string, while in Java, we use the `.length()` method. Likewise, in JavaScript, we use the `.length` property of a string.

